Test-case name: server_upgrade_cli_NEVER
This will test protection from do-release-upgrade
Ensure asked to install files (1)
Ensure Prompt=normal then: sudo sed -i 's/Prompt=never/Prompt=never/ (2)
Ensure Prompt=lts then: sudo sed -i 's/Prompt=lts/Prompt=never/ (3)
Ensure sed command fails (4)
<dl>
    <dt>Login into the system locally, or via SSH</dt>
		<dd>[FILL VERIFICATION]</dd>
    <dt>In the terminal: sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade</dt>
        <dd>APT will update</dd>
        <dd>type  (1)<em>Y</em></dd>
        <dd>New version files install</dd>
    	<dd>Check release-upgrade setting: grep '^Prompt=' /etc/update-manager/release-upgrades</dd>
        
        <dd>f Prompt=normal then: sudo sed -i 's/Prompt=never/Prompt=never/' (2)</dd>
        <dd>f Prompt=lts then: sudo sed -i 's/Prompt=lts/Prompt=never/' (3)</dd>
	<dt>Return: Prompt=normal</dt>
		<dd>[FILL VERIFICATION]</dd>
    	<dd>Check release-setting again: grep '^Prompt=' /etc/update-manager/release-upgrades</dd>
        <dd>Return: Prompt=normal</dd>
        <dd> edit manually, changing to: Prompt=never (4)</dd>
    <dt>Start the upgrade: sudo do-release-upgrade</dt>
        <dd>Checking for new Ubuntu release</dd>
        <dd>No new release be found</dd>
        
	<dt>Return to the command prompt</dt>
		<dd>[FILL VERIFICATION]</dd>
</dl>
